<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>on board • on the board</xh5><p> <i>on board—</i>1. on a ship, aircraft, or public vehicle: The life of a boy <u>on board</u> a ship isn’t one to be envied, he is at every one’s beck and call. 2. said of smb. working with an organization or a group of people: We are in the process of interviewing applicants and hope to have a new teacher <u>on board</u> soon. 3. <i>(sl.)</i> said of drink consumed by a person: With a brandy like this <u>on board</u>, I’d face the devil himself.</p><p><i>on the board—</i>1. on the notice-board to which public notices are affixed: The matriculation takes place in the Senate Hall at times indicated <u>on the board</u>. 2. on the patterned surface on which some games are played: He slowly built an assault, using every piece <u>on the board</u>. 3. belonging to the committee controlling a business: He is <u>on the board</u> of thirty companies, and can fairly claim to be the biggest hotelier in Europe.</p><p> <div class="note">Note</div> a) The expression does not correlate in meaning with the phrase <b>on the drawing board</b>—under preparation: A plan is now <u>on the drawing board</u> to build new schools in remote areas.</p><p> b) The expression does not correlate in meaning with the phrase <b>on the boards</b>—on the stage: Many of England’s most talented actors appear <u>on the boards</u> at the Swan Theater.</p> </entry>
